http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/abstract.@value:
The Precis ontology is designed to encapsulate portfolio information about an individual. This includes information that would traditionally be presented in a Resume/CV. This ontology is designed to be used with the Precis toolkit; see http://precis.rukmal.me for more.

Currently, this ontology powers a templating engine to generate dyanmic resumes, but has the potential to power other personal data driven experiences.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value:
The Precis ontology is designed to encapsulate portfolio information about an individual. This includes information that would traditionally be presented in a Resume/CV. This ontology is designed to be used with the Precis toolkit; see http://precis.rukmal.me for more.

Currently, this ontology powers a templating engine to generate dyanmic resumes, but has the potential to power other personal data driven experiences.
An accolade. This is either an 'Award' or a 'Certification'.
A specific activity, such as a specific hackathon or volunteering experience.
Type of the activity (typically a larger supergroup), such as "Hackathon" or "Volunteering".
An 'Award'; this would correspond to a traditional award, such as a Fellowship or Dean's List.
A 'Cerficiation'; this would correspond to a traditional certification, such as a CPR Rating, or the Bloomberg Market Concepts certification.
A course. This would typically be an item that is included in the "Relevant Coursework" section of a Resume/CV.

A Degree, which was completed at a specific institution, in a specific school and department. Optional media links to pictures can be included for rendering at the time of presentation. Records the year and month that the degree was (or is expected to be) awarded.

This description is associated with any other concept, providing a description. It has the capability to track priority levels, which can be used to intelligently truncate a series of descriptions when creating a Resume/CV with the command line toolkit.
Knowledge Area parent group. This would be something along the lines of "Mathematics", or "Computer Science".
An organization; this can be a company, university, a specific university department, etc.
A Portfolio item; this can be a Talk, Publication, Project, etc.
A project, such as a final year report, or a video produced for a class.
A publication, typically limited to peer reviewed articles.
An individual skill. Each skill belongs to a specific SkillGroup. For example; "Python", "R", and "Java" would all be skills, in the "Programming Languages" SkillGroup.
A Skill Group. This group can contain one or more Skills. For example, "Python", "R", and "Java" would all be in the "Programming Languages" Skill Group.
Specific subject in a Knowledge Area. This would be "Distributed Systems" in the Knowledge Area of "Mathematics", or "Real Analysis" in the "Mathematics" Knowledge Area.
A talk or presentation.
An instance of 'Work Experience'. This would be an internship/assistantship/etc.
Affiliation for a Portfolio Instance or Accolade Instance. Maps a given instance to an instance of 'Degree' or 'WorkExperience'.
The Degree which was awarded at this organization (should be a pointer to a top-level organization).
Concentration of the Degree. For example, "Finance and Business Economics", or "Computational Finance". This should point to a DBpedia entity corresponding to the Degree being awarded.
Department awarding the degree (eg: "Department of Financial Engineering", or "Department of Finance and Business Economics").
Grade (GPA; 4.0 scale) for the Degree (optional for obvious reasons :)).
The School that awards the degree. For example, this would be the "Foster School of Business", or "College of Arts and Sciences".
Type of the Degree. For example, "Bachelor of Arts", or "Master of Science". This should point to a DBpedia entity corresponding to the Degree being awarded.

The University (concept: Organization) at which the degree was awarded. This corresponds to the top-level instituion; further object properties exist to specify particular schools/departments. That is, this should point to the organization for the Univesity and not the Department. Eg: awardedAt 'University of Washington'; and should NOT be awardedAt 'Foster School of Business'.
Organization where an instance of Work Experience is taking place.
End date of a Instance. When this is included, the 'hasDate' data property corresponds to the start date.

Reference to an external resource that describes the same entity. This would typically be a reference to an existing DBpedia concept that describes the same entity. DBpedia references are not directly used here to mitigate the fact that certain user-created entitites will not have existing concepts on DBpedia, and so that we can ensure the existence of some other descriptive fields.
An 'Activity' that is a part of an 'ActivityType'.
List of authors (Human readable for now). This list should mirror the order of authors in the publication. Note that eventually this will be replaced by pointers to individual "Author" Classes.
Child organization pointer, inverse of the 'hasParentOrganization' property.
List of Collaborators (Human-readable for now). Will eventually change to a mapping to a Person entity.
Code of the course (this would imply that an organization is referenced too). For example: 420, 690, 069, etc.
Digital Object Identifier (DOI) of the publication. Including this will allow for later expansion if an inference agent is ever added to get more metadata using this.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: Digital Object Identifier (DOI) of the Publication

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Date of the instance. This implies "startDate" when a range is given with "endDate".
Code of the department (this would imply that an organization is referenced too). For example: FIN, CFRM, FE, etc.
Instance of 'Description', which describes the Thing pointing to it.
URL to image related to work experience. Can be used when displaying the information at consumption.
Additional media can be included here. For example, it could link to product/team pages, news articles, etc.

Human readable name for the entity; for display. This is the primary descriptive string for the instance it is mapped to; that is, for 'WorkExperience' it would be the job title, and for 'Publication' it would be the publication title.
Object that was affiliated with the Thing pointing to it. Here, "Object" would be typically a 'Portfolio' or 'Accolade' instance, and "Thing" would be a 'Degree' or 'WorkExperience' instance.
Pointer to a "parent" organization instance. For example, the "Foster School of Business" hasParentOrganization "University of Washington".

Priority level of the description (used for deciding truncation in toolkit). This is automatically set to the position of the string in the input "description" array of descriptions, when data is loaded using the command line tool.
A skill that is a part of a 'SkillGroup'.
Status of the publication. That is, this property should reflect a paper being "In Progress", or "Under Review".
A subject that is a part of a 'KnowledgeArea'.
Text of the description. This should be treated as a single "bullet point" on a traditional Resume/CV.
External website of the entity (not used for ontology extension; treat this as user-facing).
The ActivityType containing the Activity.
The city of the entity.
Conference/Journal name. This will eventually be replaced with a more semantically-correct representation of this information.
Country of the entity.
The knowledge area containing the subject.
Publication name containing the specific publication. As with the other fields in the 'Publication' concept, this will probably be replaced eventually.
The SkillGroup containing the Skill.
State of the entity (United States only).
A related concept. For example, an instance of 'Award' may have a 'Project', or 'Publication' that it is related to, and vice versa.
The organization at which the course was taught. This is an optional field, but ideally if this is included, the department and course codes should be too.
Grade (GPA; 4.0 scale) received in the course (optional for obvious reasons :)).
